# Premiere Pro Programmatic Cut Solutions

## Official ExtendScript Approach

According to Adobe's documentation, "There's no cut function; you'd need to change the end point of the trackItem (clip)."

The recommended method involves modifying clip endpoints:

```javascript
var myClip = app.project.sequences[0].videoTracks[0].clips[0];

if (myClip){
    var oldEnd = myClip.end;
    if (oldEnd){
        oldEnd.seconds = oldEnd.seconds + 3;
        myClip.end = oldEnd;
    }
}
```

This approach adjusts clip duration by modifying the `end` property rather than performing an actual cut operation.

## Alternative: SubClip Workaround

For more complex scenarios, create subclips with specific in/out points:

```javascript
app.project.rootItem.children[index].createSubClip(
    name, 
    startTime, 
    endTime,
    hasHardBoundaries, 
    takeAudio, 
    takeVideo
);

app.project.sequences[index].videoTracks[index].insertClip(
    projectItem, 
    time
);
```

## QE DOM Limitation

The QE (Quality Engineering) DOM includes a `razor()` method on sequence and track objects, but community reports indicate it's "unsupported" and "unrecommended" for production use.

## Key Takeaway

ExtendScript lacks native cut functionality. The endpoint modification method is the supported workaround for splitting clips programmatically.

